                        </div>
                        <div class="block-content mode">
                            <p>The following includes steps you are recommended to take after being subject to a hate crime. Note that these circumstances vary, so always remember to put your safety first.</p>
                            <ol>
                                <li><strong>Get medical assistance​</strong> if necessary and contact authorities then and there if you are in immediate danger. </li>
                                <li><strong>Note identifiable details</strong> of your attacker. (height, race, gender, weight, among other markers of physical appearance)​</li>
                                <li><strong>Prioritize your Mental Health.</strong> Coping with the trauma of a Hate Crime can be extremely difficult. Make sure you have a suiting support group to get you through these times. Take your time to come out with your story and don't allow anyone to downplay your emotions or experience.</li>
                                <li><strong>File Reports.</strong> If you've faced something other than physical aggression, like verbal harassment, know that your experience was still unacceptable and needs to be addressed. File a police report and follow-through in all of its stages of documentation to ensure your experience isn't overlooked. <a target="_blank" href="https://www.standagainsthatred.org/report">Asian Americans Advancing Justice</a> and <a target="_blank" href="https://stopaapihate.org/">Stop AAPI Hate</a>, are among two organizations where you can safely share your story and help document hate crimes against Asian Americans over the US.</li>
                            </ol>
